  "summary": "Following the unmasking of Roger Baskington-French, he confesses to his various crimes. He admits to forging a letter in Bobby's name and kidnapping Bobby at Grange by striking him on the back of the neck with a sandbag after Bobby fell from a tree. Roger also confesses to using forgery to manipulate Moira and admits he impersonated Dr. Nicholson to mock the group and observe them, noting that the real Nicholson is innocent. When Frankie asks about the identity of \"Evans,\" Roger refuses to answer.\n\nRoger suggests calling the police, claiming he has no evidence for murder. Bobby retrieves a loaded gun from Roger's pocket, and the group—Bobby, Frankie, and Budge—leaves Roger tied in the attic, locking the door behind them. While searching the house, they find Moira drugged in a bedroom next to a tray containing an alcohol lamp and a hypodermic syringe.\n\nBobby contacts the police and requests a doctor. A sergeant, an officer, and an elderly man arrive at the house. However, when the group leads the authorities to the attic to confront Roger, they find the door unlocked and the room empty. Roger has escaped through a broken skylight, leaving behind a chair positioned under the opening and a pile of cut ropes. The police superintendent becomes skeptical, viewing the entire situation as a prank, while Bobby and Frankie struggle to explain the improbable disappearance.",
